{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17607100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17607100"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:20:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:20:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15947"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15947"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8638"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72847"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8638"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15947"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58317"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8606"},{"type":"tags","id":"8672"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20685"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72847"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryological development, paraxial mesoderm segments into paired somites on either side of the developing neural tube. Each somite then differentiates into three distinct regions that give rise to specific tissues.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the correct tissue derivatives of somite differentiation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sclerotome forms vertebrae and ribs, myotome forms skeletal muscle","Dermatome forms vertebrae, sclerotome forms dermis","Myotome forms dermis, dermatome forms skeletal muscle","Sclerotome forms skeletal muscle, myotome forms vertebrae","Dermatome forms skeletal muscle, myotome forms dermis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESomites undergo segmentation into three distinct regions, each with specific developmental fates:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esclerotome\u003C/strong\u003E (ventromedial portion) develops into \u003Cstrong\u003Evertebrae and ribs\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emyotome\u003C/strong\u003E (intermediate portion) develops into \u003Cstrong\u003Eskeletal muscle\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edermatome\u003C/strong\u003E (dorsolateral portion) develops into \u003Cstrong\u003Edermis\u003C/strong\u003E of the skin\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis segmental pattern of development ensures proper spatial organisation of the musculoskeletal and integumentary systems. The process occurs in a coordinated manner under the influence of various signalling molecules.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Somites develop from paraxial mesoderm and undergo segmentation into sclerotome, myotome, and dermatome regions.","The sclerotome forms vertebrae and ribs, myotome forms skeletal muscle, and dermatome forms dermis of the skin.","Each somite segment contributes to specific tissue types in a defined spatial pattern."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58317"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15947"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58317"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T09:59:28+10:30",